post_text:
Today is our official last day of school. As we close out the 2019-2020 school year, we want to thank all of you for your support during this unparalleled time. From managing our way through COVID-19 to experiencing civil unrest throughout our country, WCSD and our Board of Education will always have the safety of our students and their families as a top priority. We take pride in our diverse student population and will continue to condemn any form of racism or discrimination.

While we have faced many difficulties and challenges that none of us could have predicted only a few short months ago, it‚Äôs important to take this time to not only mourn, remember and reflect, but also to celebrate.‚Ä¶

Westlake City Schools will honor our 2020 graduating seniors by turning on the UH-St. John Stadium lights at 8:20 p.m. (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes and 20 seconds.

While we are all experiencing uncertainty during this unprecedented time, we want our community to know that our students and graduating seniors are top-of-mind, even though they are not in our school buildings.

Join us tonight in recognizing our graduating seniors by turning on your porch light at 8:20 p.m. for 20 minutes and 20 seconds.

Please share photos of your support and your graduating senior on social media by using the hashtag #BeTheLight and tagging Westlake City Schools on Facebook, Instagram and Twitter. #WestlakePride #WeAreInThisTogether

This is an unprecedented time for our Westlake City Schools. As a result of the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic and the global, national, state and local efforts to slow the spread of the virus, the Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine issued a state-mandated three-week closure of all public, private and charter schools.

The Westlake City Schools are closing after the school day Friday, March 13, through Friday, April 3. Staff will return on Monday, March 16, to participate in a planning and preparation day for the delivery of online learning. We also will begin instituting additional cleaning of our facilities during this time.

At this time, all Westlake City Schools activities, events, athletics, clubs‚Ä¶

‚Ä¢ Some of the federal funding based on Census statistics is for services that influence students‚Äô readiness for learning, including maternal and child health programs, and housing, heating and food assistance.

post_text:
How We Express Ourselves in PreK!

During their How we express ourselves unit, WES PreK students showed they understood their central idea: Creativity can be demonstrated in different ways! through experiences like:

* pretending in their new airplane dramatic play area
* experiencing new textures at the sand table
* building structures
* listening to and learning about different musical instruments and what they sound like
* making guitars and ukuleles out of paper plates
* painting while listening to different kinds of music

They explored the key concepts: perspective and connection while learning about forms of communication, expressing individuality, and sharing and respecting others' ideas.

Learn more on our IB PYP blog at https://sites.google.com/mywlake.org/wes-ibpyp#h.p_Bdna9q0rLiLQ

Being Organized Can Help Us

As part of their How we organize ourselves unit, 1st graders learned about the organization of non-fiction chapter books. They read mentor texts and noticed tools authors use in nonfiction texts. Then they got to work researching and writing their own non-fiction chapter books. Some extended their research to other arctic animals.

They participated in STEM activities: Groups used measurement data to create life sized penguins, did a blubber experiment, and used various materials to build arctic animal homes. They also learned about Antarctica from a guest presenter.

Learn more on our IB PYP blog at https://sites.google.com/mywlake.org/wes-ibpyp#h.p_bghaUUD5AY5L

Scaffolding Learning from Concrete to Abstract

To gain conceptual understanding of fractions, 4th graders folded paper strips to compare the fractional parts of 10 different denominators.

They applied their learning in different contexts like partitioning a newspaper into fractional parts, playing fraction games and ordering written fractions.

Inquiring about things that ignited their curiosity led to discoveries of patterns and relationships between fractions! Students developed and shared strategies for ordering fractions.

Learn more on our IB PYP blog: https://sites.google.com/mywlake.org/wes-ibpyp

CLOSING THE COMPUTER SCIENCE GAP WITH TEALS

A field trip to a local software company opened the doors to Westlake High School students to learn about coding and information technology (IT) opportunities straight from industry professionals.

WHS offers Introduction to Computer Programming and Python Programming courses thanks to a partnership with Microsoft Philanthropies TEALS (Technology Education and Literacy in Schools). The program pairs computer science professionals with high school teachers to help build computer science (CS) teaching capacity.

WHS is one of 625 TEALS schools in the United States. This school year, 45 students have participated in the program.
